ings as a “refuge of last resort” in coastal areas, and to those people on locally elevated terrain. The top of a 25-story coastal high-rise in the hurricane eyewall will experience a mean wind that is about 17\% higher (or one Saffir–Simpson hurricane-scale category) than the surface or advisory value. For this reason, residents who must take refuge in coastal high-rises should generally do so at the lowest levels necessary to avoid storm surge.},
	pages = {32--44},
	number = {1},
	journaltitle = {Weather and Forecasting},
	author = {Franklin, James L. and Black, Michael L. and Valde, Krystal},
	urldate = {2022-09-08},
	date = {2003-02-01},
	note = {Publisher: American Meteorological Society
